The paper focuses on the development of a physics simulation framework for assistive robots, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The use of reinforcement learning to train the robots and the modeling of human motion and preferences for assistance suggest a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The comparison of different robots and the optimization of their performance suggest a focus on machine learning (cs.LG) and systems and control (cs.SY).
